         b'\n\t\t<div class="post-41 post type-post status-publish format-stan'
         b'dard hentry category-conference category-paper category-social-netwo'
         b'rks" id="post-41">\n\t\t\t<h2>Mapping Small Worlds</h2>\n\n\t\t\t'
         b'<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p><a href="http://www.disi.unige.it'
         b'/person/DellamicoM/research/papers/mapping_small_worlds.pdf">Here</a'
         b'> you&#8217;ll find a paper I have got accepted for <a href="http://'
         b'www.p2p2007.org">P2P2007</a>. In synthesis: given a social network o'
         b'f peers, I&#8217;m interested in constructing a &#8220;network map&#'
         b'8221; &#8212; that is, a  </p>\n<p> way of placing nodes in a k-d'
         b'imensional layout &#8212; so that nodes that are more likely to be l'
         b'inked as they are closer in the layout. The algorithm has to be dece'
         b'ntralized, and I accomplished this by requiring each node to exchang'
         b'e information only with its &#8220;friends&#8221;. Once we have such'
         b' a layout, we can use in various settings. The most obvious applicat'
         b'ion is routing in &#8220;darknets&#8221; such as Freenet (networks w'
         b'here connections are only between trusted pairs of friends): we use '
         b'the position on the layout of a node as an &#8220;address&#8221;, an'
         b'd we try to reach the destination node by routing the query to the c'
         b'losest node. This way we obtain efficient anonymous routing. Other a'
         b'pplications can be related to network analysis (e.g., we can recomme'
         b'nd to an user some content that is  &#8216;affine&#8217;: closer on '
         b'the network map), or to trust metrics (e.g., finding paths in social'
         b' networks that connect nodes to assess trust). I did this by adaptin'
         b'g an <a href="http://www.wisdom.weizmann.ac.il/~yehuda/pubs/spectral'
         b'.pdf">algorithm</a> for graph drawing based on spectral graph theory'
         b' to decentralized systems. Results are very encouraging. I think it '
         b'could be interesting to see if the same idea can be applied to oppor'
         b'tunistic networks, in order to analyze social structure and/or do ro'
         b'uting.</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetadata alt"'
         b'>\n\t\t\t\t\t<small>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tThis entry was posted'
