         b's="comment-author vcard">\n\t\t\t<img alt=\'\' src=\'http://0.grava'
         b'tar.com/avatar/236123076d9bcfb6c8fd55f0874f8d3a?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2'
         b'F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3'
         b"D32&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' /"
         b'>\t\t\t<cite class="fn"><a href=\'http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.qu'
         b"ercia/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Daniele Quercia</a></cit"
         b'e> <span class="says">says:</span>\t\t</div>\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class="'
         b'comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2'
         b'007/06/28/mapping-small-worlds/#comment-1013">\n\t\t\tJune 29, 2007 '
         b'at 12:26 pm</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<p>Very interesting paper. As Mat'
         b'teo already knows, I was thinking to use spectral layout for resourc'
         b'e discovery in p2p using tags. For now, I abandon that idea because '
         b'I may run into the problems reported in slide 4/4<br />\n<a href='
         b'"http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.quercia/others/spectral.pdf" rel="n'
         b'ofollow">http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.quercia/others/spectral.pdf'
         b'</a></p>\n<p>In the context of p2p forwarding, it would be very i'
         b'nteresting to test the algorithm under varying churn rates.</p>\n'
         b'<p>Finally, Elisa (<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.rondini/'
         b'" rel="nofollow">http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/e.rondini/</a>) might'
         b' be interested in the problem that spectral layout solves in sensor '
         b'nets:<br />\nGiven a set of sensors, and a mechanism by which eac'
         b'h sensor can estimate its distance to nearby sensors, determine the '
         b'coordinates of every sensor via sensor-to-sensor communication.<br /'
         b'>\nA relevant paper: Distributed graph layout for sensor networks'
         b'.</p>\n\n\t\t<div class="reply">\n\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n'
         b'\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\t\t<li class="comment byuser comm'
         b'ent-author-della bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1"'
         b' id="comment-1014">\n\t\t\t\t<div id="div-comment-1014" class="co'
         b'mment-body">\n\t\t\t\t<div class="comment-author vcard">\n\t\t\t<'
         b"img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/44ffd07adf8f93a0689cfb5"
         b'45fa6afdc?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503'
         b"a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 p"
         b'hoto\' height=\'32\' width=\'32\' />\t\t\t<cite class="fn"><a hr'
         b"ef='http://www.disi.unige.it/person/DellamicoM/' rel='external nofol"
         b'low\' class=\'url\'>Matteo Dell\'Amico</a></cite> <span class="says"'
         b'>says:</span>\t\t</div>\n\t\t\n\t\t<div class="comment-meta commentm'
         b'etadata"><a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/06/28/mapping-sma'
         b'll-worlds/#comment-1014">\n\t\t\tJune 29, 2007 at 1:21 pm</a>\t\t<'
         b'/div>\n\n\t\t<p>Yes, the paper about spectral layout in sensor netwo'
         b'rks was co-authored by Yehuda Koren, who is the author of the spectr'
         b'al layout algorithm I adapt. The adaptation to the distributed setti'
         b'ng, however, is different, because in the sensor case the problem ha'
         b's one obvious solution with few dimensions (the real positioning), w'
         b'hile in my case I can&#8217;t obviously rely on such luxury <img src'
         b'="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.'
         b'gif" alt=":)" class="wp-smiley" /> </p>\n<p>Regarding your proble'
         b'ms, my algorithm, when applied to tags would give each node a &#8220'
         b';subjective&#8221; view of the tagging semantic space. With the CAN '
         b'approach it looks like you are looking for an &#8220;objective&#8221'
         b'; (i.e., shared by all nodes) view.</p>\n<p>Maybe you could obtai'
         b'n something useful if you propagated the query in the social network'
         b', according to each node&#8217;s own view of &#8220;expertise&#8221;'
         b' of their friends about some area of the semantic map. Just speculat'
         b'ing&#8230;</p>\n\n\t\t<div class="reply">\n\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t'
         b'\t\t</div>\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\t\t<li class="comment by'
         b'user comment-author-dquercia even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-1'
         b'015">\n\t\t\t\t<div id="div-comment-1015" class="comment-body">\n\t'
         b'\t\t\t<div class="comment-author vcard">\n\t\t\t<img alt=\'\' src'
         b"='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/236123076d9bcfb6c8fd55f0874f8d3a?s=32"
         b'&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc'
         b"9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='"
         b'32\' width=\'32\' />\t\t\t<cite class="fn"><a href=\'http://www.cs.'
         b"ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.quercia/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Dani"
         b'ele Quercia</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>\t\t</div>\n\t'
         b'\t\n\t\t<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://mo'
         b'bblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/06/28/mapping-small-worlds/#comment-1015'
         b'">\n\t\t\tJune 29, 2007 at 1:52 pm</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<p>Yes, yo'
         b'u are right &#8211; in a CAN, one  places a given tag in a &#8220;sh'
         b'ared&#8221; semantic space. However, for the p2p discovery problem, '
         b'it would better to have a tag view tailored to each user (eg, for al'
         b'lowing personalizing search). What worries me is that p2p resource d'
         b'iscovery is a dynamic schenario (in that many resources are frequent'
         b'ly added). That is why it would be interesting to test the algorithm'
         b' under varying churn rates &#8211; it may give us some intuitions on'
         b' how robust  the algorithm in dynamic settings is <img src="http://m'
         b'obblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";'
         b'-)" class="wp-smiley" /> </p>\n\n\t\t<div class="reply">\n\t\t\t'
         b'\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\t\t<l'
         b'i class="comment byuser comment-author-della bypostauthor odd alt th'
         b'read-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-1016">\n\t\t\t\t<div id='
         b'"div-comment-1016" class="comment-body">\n\t\t\t\t<div class="com'
         b'ment-author vcard">\n\t\t\t<img alt=\'\' src=\'http://0.gravatar.co'
         b'm/avatar/44ffd07adf8f93a0689cfb545fa6afdc?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.'
         b'gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&am'
         b"p;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />\t"
         b'\t\t<cite class="fn"><a href=\'http://www.disi.unige.it/person/Dell'
         b"amicoM/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Matteo Dell'Amico</a></"
         b'cite> <span class="says">says:</span>\t\t</div>\n\t\t\n\t\t<div clas'
         b's="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.u'
         b'k/2007/06/28/mapping-small-worlds/#comment-1016">\n\t\t\tJune 29, 20'
         b'07 at 2:04 pm</a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<p>Indeed! I didn&#8217;t do ex'
         b'perimentation about that yet, but that will be stuff I&#8217;ll cert'
         b'ainly look into. I&#8217;d think it would be quite tolerant, though.'
         b' A node with lower uptime could be seen as having edges with a lower'
         b' weight, since it would interact with other nodes more rarely. And s'
         b'mall variations in the structure of the network shouldn&#8217;t chan'
         b'ge too much the solution.</p>\n\n\t\t<div class="reply">\n\t\t\t'
         b'\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</li><!-- #comment-## -->\n\t</o'
